  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Expositor's Greek Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 15:39",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "κεντυρίων",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", a Latinism = ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "centurio",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", for which Mt. and Lk. give the Greek ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἑκατόνταρχος",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐξ ἐναντίας",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "χώρας",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), right opposite Jesus, so that he could hear and see all distinctly. The thing that chiefly impressed him, according to Mk., was the manner of His death.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "οὕτως ἐξέπνευσεν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " = with a loud voice, as if life were still strong, and so much sooner than usual, as of one who, needing no Elijah to aid Him, could at will set Himself free from misery. This was a natural impression on the centurion’s part, and patristic interpreters endorse it as true and important. Victor Ant. says that the loud voice showed that Jesus died ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "κατʼ ἐξουσίαν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and Theophylact applies to the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐξέπνευσεν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the epithet ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "δεσποτικῶς",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". But it may be questioned whether this view is in accord either with fact or with sound theology. What of the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "φέρουσι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 15:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "? And is there not something docetic in self-rescue from the pangs of the cross, instead of leaving the tragic experience to run its natural course? Mt.’s explanation of the wonder of the centurion, by the external events—earthquake, etc.—is, by comparison, secondary. Schanz characterises Mk.’s account as “schöner psychologisch” (psychologically finer).",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "39–41",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The Confession of the Centurion",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "39",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "when the centurion",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] in charge of the quaternion of soldiers. See above, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Mark 15:24",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Mark 15:24",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "that he so cried out",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The whole demeanour of the Divine Sufferer, the loudness of the cry, and the words He uttered, thrilled the officer through and through. Death he must have often witnessed, on the battle-field, in the amphitheatre at Cæsarea, in tumultuous insurrections in Palestine, but never before had he been confronted with the majesty of a Voluntary Death undergone for the salvation of the world. The expression of a wondrous power of life and spirit in the last sign of life, the triumphant shout in death, was to him a new revelation.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the Son of God",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] In an ecstacy of awe and wonder “",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "he glorified God",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ",” he exclaimed, “",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "In truth this man was righteous",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "” (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 23:47",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); nay, he went further, and declared, “",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "This Man was a",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Song of Solomon of God",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".” It is possible that on bringing the Lord back after the scourging, which he superintended, the centurion may have heard the mysterious declaration of the Jews, that by their Law the Holy One ought to die, because He ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "made Himself the Son of God",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 19:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The words made a great impression on Pilate ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "then",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 19:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). But now the centurion had seen ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the end",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". And what an end! All that he had dimly believed of heroes and demigods is transfigured. This man was more. He was ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the Son of God",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Together with the centurion at Capernaum (Matthew 8) and Cornelius at Cæsarea (Acts 10) he forms in the Gospel and Apostolic histories a triumvirate of believing Gentile soldiers. The words, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "I, if I be lifted up, will draw all men unto me",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", had been already fulfilled in the instance of the penitent malefactor. They are now true of this Roman officer. The “Lion of the tribe of Judah” was “reigning from the Tree.”",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
